## API calls to chess.com

Chess.com is an internet chess server. Live online chess can be played against other users in daily, rapid, blitz or bullet time controls, with a number of chess variants also available. It is one of the largest chess platforms in the world. In this part of the assignment, we will interact with their API to scrap some data. Below is some information to start with.

You can get a list of the usernames for 10,000 players from the USA using the `R` code in the chunk below. Due to performance reasons, it doesn’t return the list of all players. Note that the returned list of usernames may change from day to day so you may not get the exact same list as others. (More information about chess.com API: <https://www.chess.com/news/view/published-data-api>)

In the code chunk below, `player_list` is a character vector of length 10,000 where each element is a username.

```{r, results='hide'}
library(httr)
library(jsonlite)
library(dplyr)
library(knitr)
library(kableExtra)
library(lme4)

response <- GET('https://api.chess.com/pub/country/US/players')

player_list <- fromJSON(rawToChar(response$content))$players
```

You can get more information for each user from their username. For instance, below is how you can get more `info`rmation and `stats` about username “`--untouchable--`”.

```{r, results='hide'}
info <- GET('https://api.chess.com/pub/player/--untouchable--')
fromJSON(rawToChar(info$content))

stats <- GET('https://api.chess.com/pub/player/--untouchable--/stats')
fromJSON(rawToChar(stats$content))
```

Write `R` code to create a data frame for the first 500 players. Each row in this data frame must represent a user with the following columns for all users.

-   `username`

-   `name` if available, `NA` if not available

-   `number of followers`

-   `location`

-   `last_online`, timestamp (you will to figure out how to convert this to a date & time; *hint*: it starts from Jan 1, 1970)

-   `rapid_last_rating` if available, `NA` if not available

-   `rapid_best_rating` if available, `NA` if not available

-   `rapid_record_win` if available, `NA` if not available

-   `rapid_record_loss` if available, `NA` if not available

-   `rapid_record_draw` if available, `NA` if not available

```{r, results='hide'}
#I'm going to test with a single player first to make sure I'm extracting everything correctly. 

test_user <- player_list[1]

#getting profiles
profile_response <- GET(paste0("https://api.chess.com/pub/player/", test_user))
profile <- fromJSON(rawToChar(profile_response$content))

#getting stats
stats_response <- GET(paste0("https://api.chess.com/pub/player/", test_user, "/stats"))
stats <- fromJSON(rawToChar(stats_response$content))


str(profile)
str(stats)
```

```{r, results='hide'}
#writing a function

#profile
get_profile <- function(username) {
  profile_response <- GET(paste0("https://api.chess.com/pub/player/", username))
  profile <- fromJSON(rawToChar(profile_response$content))
  
#stats
  stats_response <- GET(paste0("https://api.chess.com/pub/player/", username, "/stats"))
  stats <- fromJSON(rawToChar(stats_response$content))
  
#extractubg the things listed in the question
  data.frame(
    username        = username,
    name            = ifelse(is.null(profile$name),     NA, profile$name),
    followers       = ifelse(is.null(profile$followers), NA, profile$followers),
    location        = ifelse(is.null(profile$location),  NA, profile$location),
    last_online     = as.POSIXct(profile$last_online, origin = "1970-01-01", tz = "UTC"),
    
    rapid_last_rating  = ifelse(is.null(stats$chess_rapid$last$rating),  NA, stats$chess_rapid$last$rating),
    rapid_best_rating  = ifelse(is.null(stats$chess_rapid$best$rating),  NA, stats$chess_rapid$best$rating),
    rapid_record_win   = ifelse(is.null(stats$chess_rapid$record$win),   NA, stats$chess_rapid$record$win),
    rapid_record_loss  = ifelse(is.null(stats$chess_rapid$record$loss),  NA, stats$chess_rapid$record$loss),
    rapid_record_draw  = ifelse(is.null(stats$chess_rapid$record$draw),  NA, stats$chess_rapid$record$draw),
    
    stringsAsFactors = FALSE
  )
}
```

It worked, so now for the first 500 players:

```{r}
first_500 <- player_list[1:500]
all_players <- vector("list", length(first_500))

for (i in seq_along(first_500)) {
  cat("Fetching player", i, ":", first_500[i], "\n")  
  
  tryCatch({
    all_players[[i]] <- get_profile    (first_500[i])
    Sys.sleep(0.5)  
  }, error = function(e) {
    cat("  Error for", first_500[i], ":", conditionMessage(e), "\n")
    all_players[[i]] <<- NULL 
  })
}


player_df <- do.call(rbind, all_players)
```

## Identify & Remove Duplicate Files 

In this question, you’re tasked with automating a crucial task for your team in a real-world scenario. The team regularly pulls a series of datasets from a server and exports them to distinct daily folders. Each of these folders contains multiple subfolders, each housing several CSV files for analysis. Due to a system glitch, some files have been duplicated and scattered in these subfolders. As your team’s data scientist and `R` expert, your goal is to write an `R` script to identify and remove these duplicate files while keeping the original files intact. The entire folder structure houses 222 files, of which 207 are unique. Your script should also generate a table summarizing the files identified and deleted.

```{r}

folder <- "question_2"

files <- list.files(
  path = folder, 
  pattern = "\\.csv$",
  recursive = TRUE, 
  full.names = TRUE
)

cat("Total files found:", length(files)) #hopefully there are 222 


#this is the md5 hash part from StackOverflow (linked below) 

hashes <- tools::md5sum(files) #should return a named vector where names = file paths, values = hash strings 

#DUPLICATES = 

originals <- c() 
duplicates <- c() 

seen_hashes <- c() 

for (i in seq_along(files)) {
  h <- hashes[i]
  
  if (h %in% seen_hashes) {
    duplicates <- c(duplicates, files[i])
    originals <- c(originals, files[which(hashes == h)[1]])
  } else {
    seen_hashes <- c(seen_hashes, h)
  }
}

cat("Duplicates found:", length(duplicates), "\n")  #should be 15


#summary table 
duplicate_table <- data.frame(
  original_file  = originals,
  duplicate_file = duplicates,
  stringsAsFactors = FALSE
)

#it looks a little ugly so remaking it using Kable
if (nrow(duplicate_table) > 0) {
  kable(duplicate_table,
        col.names = c("Original File (Kept)", "Duplicate File (Deleted)"),
        caption   = "Duplicate Files Identified") |>
    kable_styling(bootstrap_options = c("striped", "hover", "condensed"),
                  full_width = FALSE) |>
    column_spec(1, color = "darkgreen") |>
    column_spec(2, color = "darkred")
} else {
  cat("No duplicates found — files may have already been deleted.\n")
}

if (length(duplicates) > 0) {
  for (f in duplicates) {
    file.remove(f)
    cat("Deleted:", f, "\n")
  }
}

remaining <- list.files(folder, pattern = "\\.csv$", recursive = TRUE, full.names = TRUE)
cat("Files remaining:", length(remaining), "\n")

#verifying that we have 207 files left after deletion... 
remaining <- list.files(folder, pattern = "\\.csv$", recursive = TRUE, full.names = TRUE)
cat("Files remaining:", length(remaining), "\n")  # should be 207!
```

*Note*: I used [this page on Stack Overflow](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/78214683/identify-duplicates-files-in-folder-and-subfolder) and [this article](https://medium.com/@betashorts1998/discovering-duplicate-files-a-bash-scripting-project-for-beginners-e33519b1961f) when I got stuck using my original method (using read.csv + a function based on lab 3). [This Python tutorial](https://third-bit.com/sdxpy/dup/) and [this page](https://mojoauth.com/hashing/md5-in-r#implementing-md5-in-r) were also kind of helpful. I also was struggling to have the table & deletion message work when running more than once, which is why the message says "files may have already been deleted" and the kable ended up being part of a for loop. Without using an if-then statement to create the table, I couldn't get it to render, but it seems the way I've done it, you can only run it once to see the deleted files, and then they are deleted, so running it again leads to showing nothing.  

## Multiple Models 

In this question, you are tasked with estimating and reporting the slope reliability for reading and math measures across three grades. The reliability of the slope is part of a “technical adequacy” report that is required by an external agency for these measures. You will be applying one of many different approaches to this process. Once you complete this, you will have replicated the work of researchers and test developers across the country!

To begin, download the `benchmarks.csv` file from the course repo and read in the dataset. These data are simulated, but represent individual student scores in reading and math across seasonal benchmark screenings (administered in the fall, winter, and spring) for students in Grades 3 through 5. The variables are as follows:

-   `sid`: student identifier

-   `grade`: student grade

-   `sped`: special education status of the student

-   `ethnicity`: coded race/ethnicity of the student

-   `frl`: free or reduced price lunch eligibility for the student

-   `ell`: English language learner status for the student

-   `season`: season the assessment was administered

-   `reading`: student’s reading score at the given season

-   `math`: student’s mathematics score at the given season

Reading in the data...

```{r}
library(readr)

benchmarks <- read_csv("benchmarks.csv")
```

**This is your process.**

First, recode the `season` column to a new column named `wave` so that “fall” has a value of 0, “winter” has a value of 1 and “spring” has a value of 2.

```{r}
benchmarks$wave <- ifelse(benchmarks$season == "fall",   0,
                   ifelse(benchmarks$season == "winter", 1,
                   ifelse(benchmarks$season == "spring", 2, NA)))
```

Then you are going to apply a linear mixed effect model (LME) framework to estimate the reliability of the slope separately by grade (3 through 5), and subject (math and reading).

Do not use the same code twice. If you find yourself copying/pasting code, create a function, and use that function.

Calculate the reliability of slope as the ratio of true score variance to observed total variance: . Here the true score variance estimate is derived from a linear mixed effect model based estimate of the variance in the slope (using the `{lme4}` package), and the observed score variance estimate is calculated as the variance of the ordinary least squares regression slopes for each student (using the linear model `lm()` from the `{stats}` package).

To accomplish this, you will use a `for` loop, `split` and `lapply` from the `{base}` package, **or** `map` from the `{purr}` package. Use whichever you prefer and find most elegant.

```{r}
#reliability of slope as the ratio of true score variance to observed total variance. 
#true score variance: lme4 model estimate 
#observed: variance of lm() for each student

#I'm making a function so I can do the same thing for reading & math without copy pasting... 

estimate_reliability <- function(df, subject_col) {
  
  df$score <- df[[subject_col]]
  
#numerator
  
  lme_model <- suppressWarnings(
    lmer(score ~ 1 + wave + (1 + wave | sid), REML = FALSE, data = df)
  )
  vc       <- as.data.frame(VarCorr(lme_model))
  true_var <- vc$vcov[vc$var1 == "wave" & is.na(vc$var2)]

#denominator
  
  student_slopes <- sapply(split(df, df$sid), function(student) {
    coef(lm(score ~ 1 + wave, data = student))[["wave"]]
  })
  observed_var <- var(student_slopes)
  
  data.frame(
    subject      = subject_col,
    true_var     = round(true_var,     4),
    observed_var = round(observed_var, 4),
    reliability  = round(true_var / observed_var, 4)
  )
}


#now doing this as a for loop over grade 3-5 and the two subjects 
grades   <- 3:5
subjects <- c("reading", "math")
results  <- list()

for (g in grades) {
  for (s in subjects) {
    grade_data       <- benchmarks[benchmarks$grade == g, ]
    label            <- paste0("grade", g, "_", s)
    results[[label]] <- cbind(grade = g, estimate_reliability(grade_data, s))
  }
}

```

**Numerator**

To get the `true score variance`, you will fit the following mixed-effect growth model to each subject in each grade:

-   `lme4::lmer(score ~ 1 + wave + (1+wave|sid), REML = FALSE, data = grade-subject)`

    -   Ignore all warning associated with the model fitting. We are not here concerned with nice-fitting models or things such as “*convergence*”.

-   You will then need to extract the variance of the slope; that is, the variance of the random effect of `wave`. This will be your estimated `true score variance` and serve as the numerator for the slope reliability estimate.

**Denominator**

To get the `observed score variance`, you will fit the following linear growth model individually for each student for each subject:

-   `lm(score ~ 1+ wave, data = student)`

-   You will then need to extract the fixed `slope` estimate for each student; that is, the coefficient of the `wave` variable.

-   You will then calculate the variance of those slope estimates for each grade and subject. That will be your estimated `observed score variance` and serve as the denominator for the slope reliability estimate.

To get the slope reliability estimate, divide the `true score variance` by the `observed score variance`.

Report the the slope reliability estimate for each grade and subject in a nice table.

```{r}
reliability_table <- do.call(rbind, results)
rownames(reliability_table) <- NULL

kable(reliability_table,
      col.names = c("Grade", "Subject", "True Score Var", "Observed Score Var", "Slope Reliability"),
      caption   = "Slope Reliability by Grade and Subject")
```

## Slope Reliability Function 

Write a function that takes an `lmer()` growth model object as its only argument and returns the slope reliability estimate that you just calculated. Make your function as general as possible; that is, it could work on other `lmer()` growth model objects.

Apply your function to the models in the previous question to show that it works, and show the results in a simple table.

```{r}
reliable_function <- function(model) {
  
  #numerator from above
  vc       <- as.data.frame(VarCorr(model))
  true_var <- vc$vcov[vc$var1 == "wave" & is.na(vc$var2)]
  
  #denominator
  model_data     <- model@frame       
  ids            <- unique(model_data[[names(model@flist)]])
  student_slopes <- sapply(split(model_data, model_data[[names(model@flist)]]), function(student) {
    coef(lm(score ~ 1 + wave, data = student))[["wave"]]
  })
  observed_var <- var(student_slopes)
  
  return(true_var / observed_var)
}

#testing it on the previous question 
# refit models and apply function
grades   <- 3:5
subjects <- c("reading", "math")
results2 <- list()

for (g in grades) {
  for (s in subjects) {
    df        <- benchmarks[benchmarks$grade == g, ]
    df$score  <- df[[s]]
    model     <- suppressWarnings(
      lmer(score ~ 1 + wave + (1 + wave | sid), REML = FALSE, data = df)
    )
    label          <- paste0("grade", g, "_", s)
    results2[[label]] <- data.frame(grade = g, subject = s,
                                    reliability = round(reliable_function(model), 4))
  }
}

reliability_table2 <- do.call(rbind, results2)
rownames(reliability_table2) <- NULL

kable(reliability_table2)
```

