## 95% Confidence Interval (CI) 

Now you are going to get the confidence interval around those slope reliability estimates. To do this, you will write you own bootstrapping function. Bootstrapping here is a random sample **with replacement** from the original data set with the same number of students as the original data set. Use the `base::sample()` for this task, please do **NOT** use the `dplyr::slice_sample()` function.

Your function will take five arguments: (1) a data frame (or tibble), (2) a grouping variable (in our case student id), (3) a time variable for the growth model, (4) the outcome variable for the growth model, and (5) the number of bootstrap samples.\
**Important note**. You will need to sample the same number of students, and you will need to retain the `fall`, `winter`, and `spring` `scores` for those students in order to fit the growth model. Make your function as general as possible (e.g., it could work on other data sets).

You will use your bootstrapping function to create 100 bootstrap samples for each grade and subject (normally, we would use something like 1,000 bootstraps, but that would take too long). Then you will modify the slope reliability function you wrote in **(4)** above to create a new function that takes four arguments: (1) a data frame (or tibble), (2) a grouping variable (in our case student id), (3) a time variable for the growth model, and (4) the outcome variable for the growth model. This function should return the slope reliability estimate. You will apply this function to each of your 100 bootstrap samples. This will give you 100 slope reliability estimates.

For each grade and subject, report the median slope reliability, and the 95% confidence interval (i.e., the slope reliability associated with the 2.5th percentile and 97.5th percentile). Show these results in a nice table, with 6 columns: grade, subject, *n* size, 95% CI lower bound, 95% CI upper bound, and median slope reliability estimate.

```{r}
#function 1: bootstrap n students w replacement (all time pts) 

bootstrap_sample <- function(df, id_var, n_bootstraps) {
  unique_ids  <- unique(df[[id_var]])
  sampled_ids <- sample(unique_ids, size = length(unique_ids), replace = TRUE)
  
  boot_list <- lapply(seq_along(sampled_ids), function(i) {
    student_data     <- df[df[[id_var]] == sampled_ids[i], ]
    student_data$new_id <- paste0(sampled_ids[i], "_", i) 
    student_data
  })
  
  do.call(rbind, boot_list)
}

#function 2: slope reliability; take df, id, time, and outcome as the arguments 

calc_reliability <- function(df, id_var, time_var, outcome_var) {

  lme_formula <- as.formula(paste(outcome_var, "~ 1 +", time_var, "+ (1 +", time_var, "|", id_var, ")"))
  ols_formula <- as.formula(paste(outcome_var, "~ 1 +", time_var))
  
  # numerator: random slope variance from lmer
  model    <- suppressWarnings(
    lmer(lme_formula, REML = FALSE, data = df)
  )
  vc       <- as.data.frame(VarCorr(model))
  true_var <- vc$vcov[vc$var1 == time_var & is.na(vc$var2)]
  
  # denominator: variance of OLS slopes across students
  student_slopes <- sapply(split(df, df[[id_var]]), function(student) {
    coef(lm(ols_formula, data = student))[[time_var]]
  })
  observed_var <- var(student_slopes)
  
  return(true_var / observed_var)
}

```

Main loop: bootstrap 100 times per grade x subject.

```{r}
grades      <- 3:5
subjects    <- c("reading", "math")
n_boot      <- 100
boot_results <- list()

for (g in grades) {
  for (s in subjects) {
    
    df    <- benchmarks[benchmarks$grade == g, ]
    n_stu <- length(unique(df$sid))
    label <- paste0("grade", g, "_", s)
    
    #100 reliability estimates
    boot_reliabilities <- sapply(1:n_boot, function(b) {
      boot_df <- bootstrap_sample(df, id_var = "sid", n_bootstraps = n_boot)
      calc_reliability(boot_df, id_var = "new_id", time_var = "wave", outcome_var = s)
    })
    
    boot_results[[label]] <- data.frame(
      grade      = g,
      subject    = s,
      n          = n_stu,
      ci_lower   = round(quantile(boot_reliabilities, 0.025, na.rm = TRUE), 4),
      ci_upper   = round(quantile(boot_reliabilities, 0.975, na.rm = TRUE), 4),
      median_rel = round(median(boot_reliabilities, na.rm = TRUE),          4)
    )
  }
}

#put it in a table with 6 columns: grade, subject, n size, 95% CI lower bound, 95% CI upper bound, and median slope reliability estimate.
boot_table <- do.call(rbind, boot_results)
rownames(boot_table) <- NULL

kable(boot_table,
      col.names = c("Grade", "Subject", "N Students", "95% CI Lower", "95% CI Upper", "Median slope reliability"),
      caption   = "Bootstrap Slope Reliability Estimate by Grade and Subject")

```

*Note*: I got a very large amount of singular fit warnings and the first time I ran this, the reliability function I created did not work at all. I consulted Google by pasting my code & Google AI's pop-up thing recommended using "df" (I was using "data" before, which is not smart as that is also a function in base R) and adding na.rm (as maybe it was f  ailing because some cells were missing) and this seems to have fixed it! Still getting a lot of warnings but the html said to ignore these.

